        "# **Final Project**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "M8Kmk1UiyRIH"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "The dataset I have chosen is chocolate bar ratings from 66 countries from 2006 to 2020. The source is https://www.kaggle.com/soroushghaderi/chocolate-bar-2020. It contains ratings of over 2200 individual chocolate bars, along with information on regional origin, percentage of cocoa, the variety of chocolate bean used, and where the beans were grown. The ratings are based on a scale of 1.0 to 5.0 where 1.0 is unpleasant and 5.0 is outstanding. \n",
        "\n",
        "For existing visualizations, there is a horizontal bar graph on ingredient preferences, a joint plot between ratings and amount of cocoa present in the bar and heatmap on correlations between columns. While all these visuals give some information, some of the plots are hard to analyze without the author giving some context or conclusion. \n",
        "\n",
        "Objective:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Study impact of main ingredients(percent of cocoa, cocoa butter, sugar, lecithin, vanilla, salt) on chocolate bar ratings \n",
        "\n",
        "- Identify a pattern between origin of cacao bean and maker of chocolate bar of highly rated chocolate bars (Rating > 3).\n",
        "\n",
        "I used the Altair library in Jupyter Notebook to conduct the task.\n",
        "\n",
        "The task is to explore data to find trends on the number of ingredients used, along with individual ingredients present, and the ratings of chocolate bars as well as finding relations on origin of cacao bean and company of high rated chocolate bars. \n",
        "\n",
        "The results are used to study the impact between ingredients and ratings and establish a connection between cacao bean origin and companies."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "z4XOjLdlydwW"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 1,
      "metadata": {
        "id": "EpzDXQwnwUum"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [

    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# Selecting columns that will be used for visualization and analysis\n",
        "selected_columns = [\n",
        "    'company',\n",

        "\n",
        "chocolate_df = data[selected_columns].copy()\n",
        "\n",
        "# Cleaning a few columns to be represented as boolean values  \n",
        "chocolate_df['cocoa_butter'] = chocolate_df['cocoa_butter'].replace(['have_cocoa_butter','have_not_cocoa_butter'],[True,False])\n",
        "chocolate_df['vanilla'] = chocolate_df['vanilla'].replace(['have_vanila','have_not_vanila'],[True,False])\n",
        "chocolate_df['lecithin'] = chocolate_df['lecithin'].replace(['have_lecithin','have_not_lecithin'],[True,False])\n",
        "chocolate_df['salt'] = chocolate_df['salt'].replace(['have_salt','have_not_salt'],[True,False])\n",
        "chocolate_df['sugar'] = chocolate_df['sugar'].replace(['have_sugar','have_not_sugar'],[True,False])\n",

    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "color = alt.Color('counts_of_ingredients:Q', scale=alt.Scale(scheme='redblue'), legend = alt.Legend(title='Count of Ingredients'))\n",

        "click = alt.selection_multi(encodings=['color'])\n",
        "\n",
        "rect = alt.Chart(chocolate_df).mark_circle().encode(\n",
        "    alt.X('cocoa_percent:N', title = 'Percent of Cocoa'),\n",
        "    alt.Y('rating:N', title = 'Rating of Chocolate Bar'),\n",
        "    size=alt.Size('counts_of_ingredients:Q', legend=alt.Legend(title='Size of Count')),\n",
        "    color=alt.condition(brush, color, alt.value('lightgray')),\n",
        "    tooltip=['rating:Q','company','country_of_bean_origin:O','cocoa_percent:Q','counts_of_ingredients:Q',\n",
        "             'cocoa_butter:O','vanilla:O','lecithin:O','salt:O','sugar:O'],\n",
        ").properties(\n",
        "    width = 700,\n",
        "    height = 500\n",
        ").add_selection(\n",
        "    brush\n",
        ").transform_filter(\n",
        "    click\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "bars = alt.Chart().mark_bar().encode(\n",
        "    x=alt.X('count()', title = 'Total Chocolate Bars'),\n",
        "    y=alt.Y('counts_of_ingredients:N', title = 'Count of Ingredients'),\n",
        "    color=alt.condition(click, color, alt.value('lightgray')),\n",
        "    tooltip = [alt.Tooltip('count(counts_of_ingredients)', title='Total Count')]\n",
        ").transform_filter(\n",

        ").properties(\n",

      "source": [
        "selection = alt.selection_multi(fields=['country_of_bean_origin'])\n",
        "color = alt.condition(selection,\n",
        "                      alt.Color('country_of_bean_origin:N', scale=alt.Scale(scheme='purplegreen'), legend=None),\n",
        "                      alt.value('lightgray'))\n",
        "\n",
        "base = alt.Chart(top_df).mark_bar().encode(\n",
        "    x=alt.X('company:O', title = 'Companies'),\n",
        "    y=alt.Y('count():Q', title = 'Count of Chocolate Bars'),\n",
        "    color=color,\n",
        "    tooltip=['country_of_bean_origin:O', 'company:O', 'company_location:O', 'count():Q'],\n",
        ").properties(\n",
        "    width = 700,\n",
        "    height = 400\n",
        ").transform_filter(\n",
        "    selection\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "legend = alt.Chart(top_df).mark_rect().encode(\n",
        "    y=alt.Y('country_of_bean_origin:N', axis=alt.Axis(orient='right'), title = 'Origin of Bean'),\n",
        "    color=color\n",
        ").add_selection(\n",
        "    selection\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "chart2 = alt.hconcat(\n",
        "    base,\n",
        "    legend,\n",
        "    data=top_df,\n",
        "    title={\"text\":[\"Companies with Chocolate Bar Ratings = 4\"],\n",
        "           \"fontSize\":20,\n",
        "           \"subtitle\":[\"Click on segments in Origin of Bean Legend to see what companies import from the origin country\"],\n",
        "           \"subtitleFontStyle\": \"italic\"\n",
        "          }\n",

    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "# **Key Elements of Design**\n",
        "The first main plot of 'Cocoa Percent Vs Rating' is a scatterplot that shows how percent of cocoa used effects the rating. There are two legend of color and size that is used to indicate count of ingredients. Since many of the points overlap, color and size help differentiate the data points. Each point contains detailed information that is shown by hovering over the point so that users can see the characteristics. The accompanying plots are 'Count of Ingredients Used' and 'Presence of Individual Ingredients'.\n",
        "\n",
        "'Count of Ingredients Used' is a horizontal bar chart that shows the count of ingredients used in all chocolate bars. On selecting a bar, 'Cocoa Percent Vs Rating' and 'Presence of Individual Ingredients' plots show related information to the chosen bar.\n",
        "\n",
        "'Presence of Individual Ingredients' is a group of horizontal bar charts of respective ingredients (cocoa is default ingredient) present in all chocolate bars. Presence of ingredient is given by 'true' or 'false' so that user can see how many chocolate bars contain those ingredients.\n",
        "\n",
        "By highlighting a range or area on 'Cocoa Percent vs Rating', the accompanying plots displays associated information. Users can see how many ingredients are used and break down of what individual ingredients are present. On mouseover of these plots, the specific count of chocolate bars is given.\n",
        "\n",
        "The second main plot 'Companies with Chocolate Bar Rating = 4' is a vertical bar chart that shows companies that had the highest chocolate bar ratings. The segments of each bar represent the country of origin of the cacao bean. The user can see where companies get cacao beans. The legend shows the origin of the cacao beans by country. Each segment is a country and differentiated by color. By clicking on the segments, user can see what companies get their cacao beans from that country. By hovering over the segments in the bar chart, user can get specific information about the segment such as company location, origin of cacao bean, count of chocolate bars that are made with that bean."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "CpfvLoMEzA6O"
      }
    },

        "# **Evaluation**\n",
        "\n",
        "When I first started my design, my initial goal was to find the impact of different flavors or taste on ratings of chocolate bars. After exploring the data, I realized that there was too many taste data points to use in the analysis so I chose to focus on ingredients used. \n",
        "\n",
        "I began my evaluation process using journaling studies and used my friends and family members to evaluate my design. However, I changed to thinkaloud studies approach where my evaluators directly gave me their comments and observations while using the tool. This allowed me to implement some changes that they suggested to improve the design and also discuss what they liked and what could be improved.  \n",
        "\n",
        "Some of their suggestions that I implemented are:\n",
        "- Adding titles to plots to give brief insight on what to expect from the plots.\n",
        "- Adding subtexts to all plots to explain the interactions are possible for each plot\n",
        "- Showing specific count values for 'Count of Ingredients Used' bar chart and 'Presence of Individual Ingredients' bar charts so that users can understand the amount of chocolate bars that are included.\n",
        "- Color spectrum for 'Companies with Chocolate Bar Ratings' could be expanded to easily differentiate between countries of bean origin.\n",
        "\n",
        "Their observations and comments on the design:\n",
        "- The interactive plots were simple and easy to follow. Color coding and sizing used in 'Cocoa Percent vs Rating' chart reduced the complexity of the data being present.\n",
        "- The data points are descriptive that allow user to see individual details for each point.\n",
        "- Interesting fact that the design uses ingredients as data points instead of flavors. It allows user to explore in-depth about specifics of ingredients used in chocolate bars and how it effects with the ratings.\n",
        "- It would be more informative if prices of each chocolate bar is added to show how ratings and ingredients could impact prices. This would be more helpful for businesses that manufacture and sell chocolate bars.\n",
        "- 'Companies with Chocolate Bar Ratings = 4' was slightly confusing and required bit of explanation to understand what it's trying to convey.\n",
        "- For 'Companies with Chocolate Bar Ratings = 4', segregating countries of bean origin according to the continent would help for faster analysis."

        "# **Conclusion**\n",
        "\n",
        "Some of my findings:\n",
        "- Most chocolate bars had 2 or 3 ingredients. \n",
        "- For highly rated chocolate bars, most common ingredients used were cocoa butter and sugar other than cocoa.\n",
        "- For ratings > 3.5, above 62% cocoa is popular.\n",
        "- With an increase in number of ingredients used, chocolate bars that had lower cocoa percentage got higher ratings.\n",
        "- Most popular countries of bean origin is Peru, Venezuela and Madagascar.\n",
        "- The company Soma had the most chocolate bars with high ratings.\n",
        "\n",
        "Having an another individual evaluate my design really helped in improving my visualization since they could point out elements that I missed and could add.The thinkaloud studies approach proved to be more effective since I could get direct feedback and identify the limits of the design. Also, because the people I used for evaluation are unrelated to the field, it gave me insights on how the general public might perceive my design and what knowledge they were able to gain. \n",
        "\n",
        "I think the design for plots of 'Cocoa Percent vs Rating', 'Count of Ingredients Used' and 'Presence of Individual Ingredients' gave detailed information and worked well. It allowed users to see the how many ingredients are used and the break down of ingredients present. The diverging color scheme and different sizes, used to convey count of ingredients, was able to show overlapping data points. The 'Companies with Chocolate Bar Ratings' plot could be refined more so that users won't be confused on what information the plot is showing. in future iterations, I would add more details to show what countries export the most cacao beans and how many chocolate bars are made from that bean. I would also like to add pricing data in future iterations for more in-depth analysis. "
